msgid "Overview"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/index.md:15
#, no-wrap
msgid "Throughout this book, you will find ways to implement Neovim, along with NvChad, to create a fully functional **I**ntegrated **D**evelopment **E**nvironment (IDE).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/index.md:17
#, no-wrap
msgid "I say \"ways\" because there are many possibilities. The author focuses here on using these tools for writing markdown, but if markdown isn't your focus, don't worry simply read on. If you are unfamiliar with either of these tools (NvChad or Neovim), then this book will give you an introduction to both, and if you step through these documents, you'll soon realize that you can set up this environment to be a huge help for whatever your programming or script writing needs are.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/index.md:19
#, no-wrap
msgid "Want an IDE that will help in writing Ansible playbooks? You can get that! Want an IDE for Golang? That's available too. Simply want a good interface for writing BASH scripts? It's also available.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/index.md:21
#, no-wrap
msgid "Through the use of **L**anguage **S**erver **P**rotocols and linters, you can setup an environment that is customized just for you. The best part is that once you have the environment setup, it can quickly be updated when new changes are available through the use of [lazy.nvim](https://github.com/folke/lazy.nvim) and [Mason](https://github.com/williamboman/mason.nvim), both of which are covered here.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/index.md:23
#, no-wrap
msgid "Because Neovim is a fork of `vim`, the overall interface will be familiar to `vim` users. If you aren't a `vim` user, you will pick up on the syntax of the commands quickly using this book. There's a lot of information covered here but it's easy to follow along, and once you've completed the content, you'll know enough to build your own IDE for _your_ needs with these tools.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/index.md:25
#, no-wrap
msgid "It was the author's intent **not** to break this book down into chapters. The reason is that this implies an order that must be followed and, for the most part, that's not necessary. You *will* want to start with this page, read and follow the \"Additional Software\", \"Install Neovim\" and \"Install NvChad\" sections, but from there, you can choose how you want to proceed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/index.md:26
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using Neovim as an IDE"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/index.md:29
#, no-wrap
msgid "The basic installation of Neovim provides an excellent editor for development, but it cannot yet be called an IDE; all the more advanced IDE features, even if already preset, are not yet activated. To do this we need to pass the necessary configurations to Neovim, and this is where NvChad comes to our aid. This allows us to have a basic configuration out of the box with just one command!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/index.md:31
#, no-wrap
msgid "The configuration is written in Lua, a very fast programming language that allows NvChad to have startup and execution times for commands and keystrokes that are very fast. This is also made possible by the `Lazy loading` technique used for plugins that loads them only when required.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/index.md:33
#, no-wrap
msgid "The interface turns out to be very clean and pleasant.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/index.md:35
#, no-wrap
msgid "As the developers of NvChad are keen to point out, the project is only intended to be a base on which to build your own personal IDE. Subsequent customization is done through the use of plugins.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/index.md:37
#, no-wrap
msgid "![NvChad UI](images/nvchad_rocky.png)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/index.md:38
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/plugins_manager.md:18
#, no-wrap
msgid "Main Features"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/index.md:41
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Designed to be fast.** From the choice of programming language to techniques for loading components, everything is designed to minimize execution time.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/index.md:43
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Attractive Interface.** Despite being a _cli_ application the interface looks modern and beautiful graphically, plus all the components fit the UI perfectly.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/index.md:45
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Extremely Configurable.** Due to the modularity derived from the base application (NeoVim), the editor can be adapted perfectly to one's needs. Keep in mind, however, that when we talk about customization we are referring to functionality, and not to the appearance of the interface.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/index.md:47
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Automatic update mechanism.** The editor comes with a mechanism (through the use of _git_) that allows updates with a simple `:NvChadUpdate` command.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/index.md:49
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Powered by Lua.** NvChad's configuration is written entirely in _lua_, which allows it to integrate seamlessly into Neovim's configuration by taking advantage of the full potential of the editor on which it is based.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/index.md:51
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Numerous inbuilt themes.** The configuration already includes a large number of themes to use, always keeping in mind that we are talking about a _cli_ application, themes can be selected with the `<leader> + th` key.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/index.md:53
#, no-wrap
msgid "![NvChad Themes](images/nvchad_th.png)\n"
msgstr ""

